    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-05-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-05-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="466"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d466">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Marshall Mission Files, Lot 54–D270:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Walter S. Robertson</persName> to
                        General <persName type="to">Marshall</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-05-22">22 May
                            1946</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2947.… [I have been informed] that Communist troop movements were taking place in
                    Jehol as necessary strategic military measures.…</p>
                <p>… It is evident that orders have gone out from Yenan to field team members to
                    block all investigation of Communist troop movements and this Headquarters … is
                    powerless to do anything about it. It is now also clear why Chou En-lai refused
                    to grant freedom of movement to field teams. The agreement signed on 14 May in
                    deference to his representations and as a test of Communist good faith has
                    already been rendered valueless for emergency situations.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
